# Performance Guardrails

## Goals
- Prevent regressions in latency, throughput, and resource use.
- Keep patterns consistent across services.

## Timeouts and Limits (defaults)
- HTTP client calls: set explicit timeout (never infinite). Typical: 2–5s.
- DB health checks: 2s (see `apps.core.db`).
- Slow request warning threshold: 1s (log WARNING; adjust per endpoint if needed).
- Page size: default 20, max 100 (see pagination utils).
- Request size limit: configured in middleware; keep small unless justified.

## Database Guardrails
- Use SQL-level pagination for lists.
- Avoid N+1: eager load relationships where needed.
- Avoid selecting `*`—select only needed columns.
- Index frequently queried columns and FKs.
- Keep transactions short; avoid long-held locks.

## Caching Considerations
- Cache only when approved (see global rule: ask before adding cache/idempotency).
- Invalidate on writes; set TTLs; avoid caching sensitive or high-churn data.

## Concurrency and Async
- Use async for all I/O; avoid blocking calls in async contexts.
- Use `asyncio.gather` for independent concurrent tasks, but bound fan-out.
- Set worker counts and DB pool sizes deliberately (no unbounded defaults).

## Logging and Metrics for Performance
- Log slow requests (> threshold) with route and duration (no PII).
- Emit request duration metrics (histograms) with low-cardinality labels.
- Track DB query durations and pool saturation if available.

## Payloads and Serialization
- Use `ORJSONResponse` for JSON.
- Avoid large payloads; paginate/stream if needed.
- Validate and constrain upload/download sizes.

## Testing and Regression Prevention
- Add perf-sensitive tests or benchmarks for hot paths when feasible.
- Guardrail checks in CI (lint for pagination, max page size, and timeouts where practical).
- Document endpoint-specific thresholds if they differ from defaults.

## Common Anti-Patterns to Avoid
- Blocking I/O in async routes/services.
- Missing pagination on list endpoints.
- Large unbounded queries or responses.
- Excessive logging in hot paths.
- Unbounded concurrency/fan-out.
